Alright â€” the tricky bit here is that Excel pivots wonâ€™t magically â€œlook across rowsâ€ and figure out if all actions for a Risk Event were closed by their due date.
We have to first prep the data so each Risk Event in a given month has a single remediation status.

â¸»

Step 1 â€“ Pre-calculate â€œFully Remediated on Timeâ€

Youâ€™ll need a helper column in your dataset (before pivoting):
	1.	Group by Risk Event ID + Month of Action Due Date
	2.	For each group:
	â€¢	Count total actions â†’ Total_Actions
	â€¢	Count actions closed on or before their due date â†’ Closed_On_Time_Actions
	â€¢	If Total_Actions = Closed_On_Time_Actions â†’ mark as â€œFully Remediated On Timeâ€
	â€¢	Else â†’ â€œNot Fully Remediatedâ€

You can do this in Excel with:
	â€¢	Power Query (Group By â†’ All Rows â†’ Add column comparing counts)
	â€¢	or Pivot Table pre-step in a separate table.

â¸»

Quick Excel Formula Approach (no Power Query)

If your data has:
	â€¢	Risk Event ID = A
	â€¢	Action Due Date = B
	â€¢	Action Closed Date = C

	1.	Add helper column Closed_On_Time:

=IF(C2<=B2,1,0)


	2.	Add another column MonthDue:

=EOMONTH(B2,0)


	3.	Create a Summary Table with UNIQUE combinations of Risk Event ID + MonthDue.
	4.	Use COUNTIFS to get:
	â€¢	Total_Actions = COUNTIFS(RiskEventID, X, MonthDue, Y)
	â€¢	Closed_On_Time_Actions = SUMIFS(Closed_On_Time, RiskEventID, X, MonthDue, Y)
	5.	In another column:

=IF(Total_Actions=Closed_On_Time_Actions,"Fully Remediated","Not Fully Remediated")



Now you have one row per Risk Event per month with its remediation status.

â¸»

Step 2 â€“ Build the Pivot for % Remediated

Once you have the cleaned summary table:
	â€¢	Rows â†’ MonthDue
	â€¢	Values â†’ Count of Risk Event IDs
	â€¢	Columns â†’ Remediation Status (Fully Remediated / Not Fully Remediated)
	â€¢	Value Field Settings â†’ Show Values As â†’ % of Row Total

This will give:

Month	Fully Remediated	Not Fully Remediated
Jan 2025	75%	25%
Feb 2025	82%	18%


â¸»

